Chap. 22 seems to be naturally ended at multitudo 3 but, on the other hand, there is a contrast drawn between the prescribed ritual (ritus 22. 8) of the various cults and the eults themselves (23. l). The sistrum, scattered limbs, and empty tomb are the symbolio things connected with the worship of Isis, just as the barefooted priests with the worship of Pan, the Salii with that of Mars, or the Galli with that of Cybele. Hence, if this passage is genuine, its natural place is the section dealing with the ritus. Several edd. correct it and include it in c. 23.
